{% extends "@core/docs/_layout.twig" %}

{% block doc_content %}
    <h1>PHPUnit Testing Suite</h1>
    <p>
        Rhapsody ships with a ready‑to‑run testing environment built on PHPUnit.
        You get a robust base <code>TestCase</code> class that integrates with the
        framework's container, HTTP routing, and Doctrine ORM, plus convenient traits
        and mocks to speed up your feature and unit tests.
    </p>

    <div class="bg-blue-100 border-l-4 border-blue-500 text-blue-700 p-4 my-4">
        <strong>Quick Start:</strong> Run <code>./vendor/bin/phpunit</code> from the project root.
        All tests are located in the <code>tests/</code> directory.
    </div>

    <hr>

    <h2>Configuration Setup</h2>
    <p>
        The <code>phpunit.xml</code> file is already provided in the project root.
        It points to <code>tests/bootstrap.php</code> as the bootstrap file.
        Make sure your <code>bootstrap.php</code> defines the <code>ROOT_DIR</code>
        constant and loads Composer's autoloader:
    </p>
    <pre><code class="language-php">&lt;?php
// tests/bootstrap.php
define('ROOT_DIR', dirname(__DIR__));
require_once ROOT_DIR . '/vendor/autoload.php';
</code></pre>
    <p>
        This file is executed before every test run, ensuring that your application's
        classes are autoloaded and any global constants are defined.
    </p>

    <hr>

    <h2>Base Test Case &amp; Productivity Traits</h2>
    <p>
        All your test classes should extend <code>Rhapsody\Core\Testing\TestCase</code>.
        This base class automatically boots a fresh application container in
        <code>setUp()</code>, so you have access to all registered services.
    </p>

    <h3>1. Database Isolation via <code>RefreshesDatabase</code></h3>
    <p>
        To prevent test data from interfering between tests, use the
        <code>RefreshesDatabase</code> trait. It provides a <code>setUpDatabase()</code>
        method that drops and recreates all tables based on your Doctrine entity metadata.
    </p>
    <pre><code class="language-php">namespace Tests\Feature;

use Rhapsody\Core\Testing\TestCase;
use Rhapsody\Core\Testing\Traits\RefreshesDatabase;

class UserTest extends TestCase
{
    use RefreshesDatabase;

    protected function setUp(): void
    {
        parent::setUp();
        $this->setUpDatabase(); // Rebuilds schema
    }

    public function test_user_can_be_created(): void
    {
        $user = new User(['email' => 'test@example.com']);
        $this->app->get('entityManager')->persist($user);
        $this->app->get('entityManager')->flush();

        $this->assertNotNull($user->getId());
    }
}
</code></pre>
    <div class="bg-yellow-100 border-l-4 border-yellow-500 text-yellow-800 p-4 my-4">
        <strong>Performance Tip:</strong> For large test suites, consider using transactions
        instead of full rebuilds. The trait can be extended to support transaction‑based
        rollbacks – check the framework's advanced testing guide.
    </div>

    <h3>2. Fluent HTTP Response Assertions</h3>
    <p>
        The <code>call()</code> method dispatches a request through the router and returns
        a <code>TestResponse</code> object. This wrapper offers a fluent interface for
        common assertions, making your tests more readable.
    </p>
    <pre><code class="language-php">public function test_homepage_returns_successful_response(): void
{
    $this->call('GET', '/')
         ->assertOk()                  // status 200
         ->assertSee('Welcome to Rhapsody')
         ->assertDontSee('Error');
}

public function test_login_validation_fails(): void
{
    $response = $this->call('POST', '/login', [
        'email' => 'invalid',
        'password' => 'short',
    ]);

    $response->assertStatus(302)       // redirect
             ->assertSessionHasErrors(['email', 'password']);
}
</code></pre>
    <p>
        Available assertion methods include:
    </p>
    <ul>
        <li><code>assertOk()</code>, <code>assertStatus($code)</code></li>
        <li><code>assertSee($text)</code>, <code>assertDontSee($text)</code></li>
        <li><code>assertJson(array $data)</code>, <code>assertJsonMissing(array $data)</code></li>
        <li><code>assertRedirect($uri)</code></li>
        <li><code>assertSessionHas($key, $value)</code>, <code>assertSessionHasErrors()</code></li>
    </ul>

    <h3>3. Dependency Injection Container Mocks</h3>
    <p>
        Two helper methods (<code>swap()</code> and <code>mock()</code>) allow you to
        substitute real services with test doubles.
    </p>
    <ul>
        <li>
            <strong><code>swap($abstract, $instance)</code></strong> – replaces the container's
            binding for the given interface or class with your own object.
        </li>
        <li>
            <strong><code>mock($abstract, callable $mockDefinition)</code></strong> – creates
            a PHPUnit mock, lets you configure expectations, and then swaps it into the container
            in one step.
        </li>
    </ul>
    <pre><code class="language-php">public function test_payment_flow(): void
{
    // Swap with a custom fake
    $fakeGateway = new FakePaymentGateway();
    $this->swap(PaymentGatewayInterface::class, $fakeGateway);

    // Or create a mock with expectations
    $this->mock(PaymentGatewayInterface::class, function ($mock) {
        $mock->expects($this->once())
             ->method('charge')
             ->with(100.00)
             ->willReturn(true);
    });

    $this->call('POST', '/checkout', ['amount' => 100])
         ->assertOk()
         ->assertSee('Payment Successful');
}
</code></pre>
    <p>
        This approach allows you to test controller logic without hitting external APIs
        or relying on real implementations.
    </p>

    <hr>

    <h2>Testing with reCAPTCHA</h2>
    <p>
        When testing forms that include a reCAPTCHA widget, you can mock the validation
        rule or the <code>Recaptcha</code> helper to always return success. For example:
    </p>
    <pre><code class="language-php">use Rhapsody\Core\Helpers\Recaptcha;

public function test_registration_with_recaptcha(): void
{
    // Make the verify() method always return true
    $this->mock(Recaptcha::class, function ($mock) {
        $mock->method('verify')->willReturn(true);
    });

    $this->call('POST', '/register', [
        'name' => 'John Doe',
        'email' => 'john@example.com',
        'password' => 'secret123',
        'password_confirmation' => 'secret123',
        'g-recaptcha-response' => 'dummy-token', // still required, but validation passes
    ])->assertRedirect('/dashboard');
}
</code></pre>
    <p>
        Alternatively, you can disable the rule entirely in your test environment by
        using a conditional validation rule (e.g., only apply <code>recaptcha</code>
        if <code>APP_ENV !== 'testing'</code>).
    </p>

    <hr>

    <h2>Additional Tips</h2>
    <ul>
        <li><strong>Test coverage:</strong> Use <code>phpunit --coverage-html coverage/</code> to generate an HTML coverage report (requires Xdebug or pcov).</li>
        <li><strong>Parallel testing:</strong> For large suites, consider using <code>paratest</code> or PHPUnit's process isolation.</li>
        <li><strong>Environment separation:</strong> Create a separate <code>.env.testing</code> file for test‑specific settings (e.g., database credentials, mail drivers).</li>
        <li><strong>Custom assertions:</strong> Extend <code>TestResponse</code> to add your own helpers for domain‑specific responses.</li>
    </ul>

    <hr>

    <h2>Common Pitfalls</h2>
    <ul>
        <li><strong>Container not refreshed:</strong> Each test method runs in a fresh container. Do not rely on global state between tests.</li>
        <li><strong>Database not rebuilt:</strong> Always call <code>setUpDatabase()</code> if using <code>RefreshesDatabase</code>. You can also call it in <code>setUp()</code> or in a <code>@before</code> annotation.</li>
        <li><strong>Mocking final classes:</strong> PHPUnit cannot mock final classes; use <code>swap()</code> with a custom implementation instead.</li>
        <li><strong>Response content missing:</strong> Ensure the router actually returns a response; if a controller throws an exception, the test will fail early.</li>
    </ul>

    <p>
        For further details, refer to the official PHPUnit documentation and the
        framework's source code in <code>Rhapsody\Core\Testing</code>.
    </p>
{% endblock %}